{[%evp 0,32,80,30,69,-10,28,16,28,25,26,39,36,36,65,11,43,50,50,75,56,47,69,69,
47,47,36,3,6,-29,-31,-17,-14,-14,-10]} 1. e4 c6 2. f4 e5 $5 {Black usually
replies 2...d5 in all Caro-Kann variations, but we can make an exception in
this case because rare line 1...e5 is really interesting against 2.f4. In fact,
it is as if Black plays the move 2...c6 against the King's gambit! This would
probably be a great surprise for our opponent who may not be ready to play
King's gambit.} (2... d5 {is the main move.}) 3. Nf3 {Besides this move, White
has several alternatives. Of course, Black's plan is to continue in Caro-Kann
spirit with ...d7-d5 in any event.} (3. fxe5 $4 Qh4+ {is a beginner's trap
that White has to watch out for in most variations of the King's gambit.} 4.
Ke2 (4. g3 Qxe4+ $19) 4... Qxe4+ 5. Kf2 Bc5+ $19) (3. Nc3 exf4 4. Qf3 (4. Nf3
d5 5. d4 {transposes to 3.Nf3}) (4. d4 $6 {This move has some sense since
Steinitz played very similar way in King's gambit. But still, in modern
opening theory this kind of play seems too risky.} Qh4+ $1 5. Ke2 d5 6. Nf3 Qe7
$1 $146 7. e5 f6 $5 $17 {[%csl Re5,Gf4][%cal Gb8d7,Gg7g5]}) (4. Bc4 {This is a
common type of development in King's gambit, planning to answer 4...Qh4+ with
5.Kf1. Black can use his first move to push white pieces back with:} b5 $5 5.
Bb3 b4 6. Nce2 {and only now take space in the center:} d5 7. exd5 Qh4+ $5 $146
8. Kf1 Bd6 9. Qe1 $1 Qd8 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] White pieces look
ridicoulous here and Black will have initiative following Ne7, 0-0 etc.}) 4...
d5 5. d4 {Here, I can propose a simple novelty:} dxe4 $5 $146 6. Qxe4+ Be7 7.
Qxf4 (7. Bxf4 {is slightly inferior as white queen is exposed on the e-file
after} Nf6 8. Qd3 O-O) 7... Nf6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 {White should cover his
king.} (9. Nf3 $6 Bd6 10. Qh4 Re8+ $15) 9... Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4]} 10. a3 Bg4 11.
O-O {[%cal Ge2g3]} Bh5 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gh5g6,Ga6c7] having developed all his
pieces, Black has no problems.}) (3. d4 {is very ambitious, but Black has a
good reply:} exd4 4. Qxd4 d5 $1 5. Nc3 (5. exd5 $2 cxd5 {leads to a pawn
structure where f4-pawn is weakness.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Bb5 Be7 $17)
5... Nf6 ({Another option for Black is} 5... dxe4 $5 $146 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nxe4
Bf5 8. Ng3 $1 Bxc2 9. Kd2 $1 Ba4 10. b3 Bb5 11. Bxb5 cxb5 12. Bb2 Nc6 {[%cal
Gd8c7] when White has compensation, but not more than that.}) 6. e5 Ng4 7. Nf3
Nd7 {[%cal Gf8c5] Black is ready to develop his bishop to the important g1-a7
diagonal, which gives him initiative.} 8. h3 $146 (8. f5 $2 Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Qe7
10. Bf4 f6 $19) 8... Bc5 9. Qd2 Nf2 10. Rh2 f5 {[%cal Gf2e4] Black has no
problems since he can always secure his knight on e4-square, so I believe that
he is practically better.}) ({In case of quiet} 3. d3 exf4 4. Bxf4 d5 5. exd5
cxd5 6. Nf3 Bd6 {Black has easy development. I don't believe that White can
pose any problems in the opening with such an approach.}) 3... exf4 (3... d5 $5
{is also interesting.}) 4. d4 d5 {Naturally, Black gets his pawn to d5.} 5. Nc3
({In case of} 5. e5 {a typical way to protect the f4-pawn in the King's gambit
is} g5 $1 {and if} 6. h4 g4 7. Ng1 {Black should undermine the e5-pawn with} f6
$5 $146 8. Bxf4 Bh6 $1 9. Qd2 Bxf4 10. Qxf4 fxe5 11. Qxe5+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Nxe7
$15 {[%csl Rg3,Gg4,Rh4][%cal Ge7f5] As a result, Black has very nice control
of the kingside and central squares. The g4-pawn limits white knight, so
maneuver Ng1-f3-e5 is not possible.}) (5. Bxf4 dxe4 6. Ne5 $6 {Only this move
has been seen in practice,} ({but a new possibility} 6. Ng5 $5 $146 {deserves
attention. Black should have no problems if he answers:} Bf5 (6... Nf6 $2 7.
Bc4 Nd5 8. O-O f5 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Ngxe4 $1 $16) 7. Bc4 Bg6 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nc3 Be7
10. Ncxe4 O-O {[%cal Gb8d7]}) 6... Nd7 $1 $146 7. Nd2 Nxe5 8. dxe5 f5 $5 {
In this unusual position, White still has to prove if he has compensation.}) (
5. exd5 {transposes to an interesting line from King's Gambit's.} Bd6 (5...
cxd5 {is also possible, but the main line is more interesting.}) 6. Nc3 (6.
dxc6 {is a little bit premature as it facilitates Black's development.} Nxc6 7.
Be2 $1 (7. Bc4 {although this move has been played the most, it is not so good.
} Nf6 8. Qe2+ Kf8 $1 9. O-O Bg4 10. c3 h6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7]} (10... g5
11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 $1 $13)) 7... Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] with an
unclear position. The knight is headed toward f5 and e3.}) 6... Ne7 (6... Nf6 {
is transposing to main line. 6...Ne7 is an extra alternative.}) 7. dxc6 ({
Alternatively,} 7. Bc4 cxd5 8. Bxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 O-O {is fine for
Black.} 11. O-O Bg4 (11... Rd8 $5 $146 {is also possible, to put the pressure
on d4-pawn.}) 12. Ne4 Bc7 {It is important to keep f4-pawn defended.} 13. Nf2
Bh5 14. Nh3 Qf5 15. c3 $1 $146 {This is better} ({than} 15. Qd2 f6 $1 $146 16.
Nxf4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Qxc2 $15) 15... Nc6 {with an unclear position.}) 7... Nbxc6
{Black has an easy piece development, while limiting activity of opponent's
pieces thanks to his f4-pawn.} 8. Bc4 (8. Ne4 {can be answered with attack on
the c2-pawn:} Bf5 $5 9. Bd3 Nb4 $1 $146 10. Nxd6+ Qxd6 11. Bxf5 Nxf5 {and
Black should not have problems even if White trades into the endgame:} 12. Qe2+
Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {[%cal Gb4d5]} 14. Kd2 f6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5] This is an
important move because we are planning to give support to the strong f4-pawn
with g7-g5. White has poor piece coordination, so the position remains unclear.
}) (8. d5 {looks better than it actually is. This pawn-push also leaves
weaknesses.} Nb4 9. Bc4 O-O $1 {This is an introduction into the following
active and strong idea:} 10. a3 b5 $1 {Black uses his lead in development to
initiate concrete play.} 11. Bb3 (11. Bxb5 $2 {looks good at first, but after}
Nbxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 {none of White's tempting options work:} 13. c4 ({
Importantly, in case of} 13. Bc6 Nf6 $1 $146 {Black obtains a winning attack
with:} 14. Bxa8 Re8+ $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc8a6,Gd6c5]}) 13... Bb7 $1 $146 14.
O-O a6 $17) ({Black should not be afraid of} 11. Nxb5 $146 Nbxd5 12. Nxd6 Qxd6
13. O-O Ba6 $1 $15) 11... Na6 12. Nxb5 $6 (12. O-O $1 $146 {is an improvement
over White's play. Still, Black has a good response:} Bg4 $1 13. Nxb5 Qb6+ 14.
Nbd4 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] and White's position is difficult to play as his pieces
are pinned.}) 12... Bc5 $1 $146 {This novelty changes the evaluation. If White
wants to castle, he has to play} 13. Nbd4 {when Black gets his pawn back with
a better position.} Nxd5 $17) 8... O-O 9. O-O ({White can not trouble Black
with} 9. Ne2 $6 {because} Qc7 $1 $146 {not only protects the f4-pawn, but also
sets up some tactical traps, such as} 10. O-O Nxd4 $1) (9. Ne4 Bc7 10. O-O Ng6
{is just a transposition to 9.0-0}) 9... Ng6 $5 {This is a good square for the
knight.} (9... Bf5 $5 {is an interesting alternative.}) 10. Ne4 Bc7 11. c3 Bg4
{with a double-edged and very interesting position.}) 5... Nf6 6. exd5 Bd6 {
We can see some similarities with 5.exd5 line. In this case, the knight is
developed to f6 instead of e7.} 7. Qe2+ $1 {The endgame is White's best bet
because he suffers from lack of space for his pieces in the middlegame, and he
can win the f4-pawn more easily when there are less pieces on the board.} (7.
Bc4 $6 cxd5 8. Bxd5 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Bb3 Bg4 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Gd6,Gf4] and
Black has nice activity. White's main problem is that his dark-squared bishop
has no ideal place to go.}) (7. dxc6 $6 {is quite similar to 7.Bc4} Nxc6 8. Bc4
O-O 9. O-O Bg4 $15) 7... Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. Bc4 ({Alternatives are also
harmless for Black:} 9. dxc6 Nxc6 10. Bd2 (10. Nb5 Bb8 11. Bd2 a6 12. Na3 Bf5
$1 $146 {Black is slightly better.}) 10... Bg4 {[%cal Gh8d8] Black has no
problems.}) ({and} 9. Ne5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5+ cxd5 11. Bxf4 Nc6 12. O-O-O Bf5 $11) {
It is important to remember that we often meet Bc4 with} 9... b5 {with a
forced sequence:} 10. Bb3 b4 11. Ne2 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 cxd5 13. Bxf4 Nc6 {That
leads to a more balanced endgame, which is still very pleasant for Black. The
best continuation for White is} 14. a3 $1 $146 ({while after} 14. O-O-O f6 $1
$146 {Black is slightly better.}) 14... bxa3 15. Bxd6+ Kxd6 16. Rxa3 f6 $5 {
and Black should have no problems once he develops his pieces and activates
his rooks.} *

