{[%evp 0,30,31,10,55,34,42,3,21,-9,-9,-4,-2,22,2,7,5,14,9,9,6,6,19,-12,14,-2,
-23,-14,-13,-6,-8,-15,-15]} 1. e4 c6 2. b3 e5 $5 {Once again, we take the
opportunity to transpose into 1.e4 e5 territory under favorable circumstances.
In this case, I believe that our c6-move makes more sense than White's b3-move.
At the same time, it makes sense to block the diagonal for the b2-bishop.} 3.
Bb2 ({In case of} 3. Nf3 {I can suggest} Nf6 $146 {which ends up being a
strange kind of Petroff defense after:} 4. Nxe5 Nxe4 5. Bb2 ({In principle,
White would like to play} 5. Qe2 $6 {but in this case it does not work as
intended:} d5 6. Bb2 (6. d3 $2 {would normally win for White, but with the
pawn on b3 it fails to:} Bb4+ 7. Kd1 O-O 8. dxe4 dxe4+ 9. Bd2 Qd4 $19) (6. f3
$2 {has a different problem:} Qh4+ $1 7. g3 Nxg3 8. hxg3 Qxh1 9. Ng6+ Be6 10.
Nxh8 Nd7 $17 {[%csl Rh8]}) 6... Be7 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 f6 $5 9. Nd3 Re8 $15 {
and Black's setup looks more meaningful than White's ineffective fianchettoed
bishops.}) 5... Be7 $5 {Simple development. Black should not experience any
problems, for example:} 6. Bd3 $5 Nc5 7. Be2 d6 8. Ng4 Ne6 9. O-O O-O $11) 3...
Nf6 $1 $146 {It's very interesting to see that a new move can be recommended
at such an early stage - already on move 3.} 4. Bxe5 (4. Nf3 {transposes to 3.
Nf3 after} Nxe4 5. Nxe5 Be7) 4... Nxe4 $1 {Now we have a position that is very
similar to the note after 3.Nf3, only with the bishop on e5, rather than the
knight.} 5. Qe2 {The most principled, though Black has a good reply.} (5. Nf3 {
is slower, but also playable.} d5 6. Qe2 (6. d3 Nf6 7. Qe2 Be6 8. Ng5 Nbd7 {
transposes to 6. Qe2.}) 6... Be6 (6... f6 $5 {is riskier, but deserves
attention, as well.} 7. Bb2 ({The point is that after} 7. Bxb8 Rxb8 8. d3 f5 {
[%cal Gd8f6,Gf8b4]} 9. dxe4 fxe4 $44 {Black actually obtains excellent
compensation for the piece due to his central pawns, weak dark squares and
poor development for White.}) 7... Kf7 $5 {This was another point of 6...f6.
Black solves the problem of the pin in an original way. One possible line goes:
} 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. Nxe4 Re8 10. Ne5+ Kg8 11. Qh5 Nd7 $1 12. Bd3 $1 Nxe5 13. Nxf6+
gxf6 14. Qxh7+ Kf8 {and this probably ends with perpetual checks.}) 7. d3 Nf6
8. Ng5 {This now looks like one of the topical variations of the French
defense exchange variation. Black does not mind the exchange on e6, in
principle.} Nbd7 $5 9. Nxe6 (9. Bb2 $6 {is much too slow due to:} Qa5+ $1 10.
Qd2 (10. Nd2 $2 O-O-O 11. Nxe6 Re8 $17) 10... Bb4 11. Bc3 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qc7 13.
Nxe6 fxe6 14. Be2 O-O-O $15 {and Black completes his development, having a
better piece coordination as well.}) (9. Bc3 {prevents the check on a5, but
feels a bit unnatural.} Nc5 $5 {Preparing d5-d4, while also covering the
e6-bishop makes a lot of sense here.} (9... Qb6 $5 {is a more enterprising
possibility:} 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Kd8 $44 {and White may face problems
down the e-file.}) (9... Qe7 {[%cal Ge6g4] looks quite reasonable, as well.}
10. Nxe6 Qxe6 11. Qxe6+ fxe6 12. g3 Bd6 13. Nd2 g5 {[%cal Ge8f7,Ga7a5] Having
limited white bishop pair, Black should be doing fine in this multi-piece
endgame.}) 10. g3 (10. Nxe6 $2 {is not the ideal way to exchange on e6.} Nxe6
$17 {[%cal Gd5d4,Yd8c7,Yf8d6,Ye8g8,Ye8c8]}) 10... d4 11. Bb2 Be7 {and Black
has no problems.} (11... Nxd3+ $5 12. Qxd3 Qa5+ 13. Qd2 Bb4 14. c3 dxc3 15.
Nxc3 Rd8 {complicated position. Black has huge compensation.})) 9... fxe6 10.
Bb2 {White is trying to claim the bishop pair advantage, also hoping to
exploit the pressure on the e-pawn. However, Black has his own advantages, too.
} Qa5+ (10... e5 {is also an option, since it would be extremely risky for
White to take the pawn due to the attack on the e-file and weak dark squares.})
11. Nd2 Ba3 $5 {Eliminating the strong white bishop. Black does not mind
giving the e-pawn, since after:} 12. Qxe6+ Kd8 13. O-O-O Qb4 {[%cal Ga7a5,
Ga5a4] his king is completely safe on d8 and he has active play all over the
board. Sample variations are:} 14. Nb1 ({and} 14. Qe1 Re8 15. Be2 Qe7 16. Bf3
Qb4 17. Be2 {Black can force a draw if he wants to,} (17. Qf1 $6 Ne5 $1 $15 {
[%cal Ga7a5]}) {but he can also continue:} 17... a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 18. Nb1
$1 Qf4+ 19. Qd2 Bxb2+ 20. Kxb2 Qd4+ 21. c3 Qxf2 {with no problems whasoever.})
14... Bxb2+ 15. Kxb2 Qd4+ 16. c3 Qxf2+ 17. Rd2 Qh4 {and Black should be happy
after returning the sacrificed pawn, as his position remains safe and sound.})
5... Qe7 $5 6. Qxe4 d6 {Black attempts a similar maneuver to retrieve the
piece in the Petroff defense, as well. Here, it is clearly a better version
for him as he wins the bishop pair, likely obtaining full compensation for the
pawn.} 7. f4 (7. d4 Nd7 8. Nf3 ({In case of} 8. f4 dxe5 9. fxe5 {Black will
naturally undermine the pawn center with} f6 10. Nf3 fxe5 11. dxe5 {and now he
has a very strong sequence:} Nf6 $1 12. Qd4 Bf5 $1 13. Bd3 Rd8 {activating his
pieces and achieving full compensation after} 14. Qc4 Bxd3 15. cxd3 Nd5 {
[%cal Gd5e3]} 16. Kf2 Qd7 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd5b6]} (16... g5 {is also possible.
})) 8... dxe5 9. dxe5 {In this case, the most convenient way of targeting the
e5-pawn is:} g6 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7]} 10. Nbd2 Bg7 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Be2 {
and now Black can even take the initiative with:} Qb4+ $1 13. Kf1 b5 $5 14.
Qxc6 Rb8 15. Ne3 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Ge5]}) (7. Nf3 Nd7 8. d4 {
transposes to 7.d4}) 7... dxe5 8. fxe5 ({The endgame after} 8. Qxe5 Qxe5+ 9.
fxe5 Bf5 {can't be worse for Black.} 10. Nc3 Ba3 {[%cal Gf5c2] preventing
castling and preparing Bxc2 looks the best.} ({Simple} 10... Nd7 11. O-O-O
O-O-O {is also playable.}) ({However,} 10... Bxc2 $2 {is too greedy.} 11. d3
$18 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ge1d2]}) 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. cxd3 Na6 {and if anyone can be
better, it is Black.}) 8... g6 $5 {A multi-purpose move, not only preparing
Bf8-g7, but also Bc8-f5.} 9. Nf3 Bf5 10. Qe3 Nd7 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. Nd4 {This is
the critical move.} ({In case of} 12. O-O-O O-O $1 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 13. d4 {
White is up a pawn, but his dark squares are too exposed in the long run. I
prefer Black after} f6 14. Bc4+ Kh8 $15 {[%csl Re5]}) 12... Bg4 $5 {This will
lead to a balanced endgame almost by force.} ({Another playable option is} 
12... Nxe5 13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. Be2 O-O 15. O-O Rae8 {when Black can surely
compensate for his structural weakness with active piece play.}) 13. h3 Bxe5
14. hxg4 Bxd4 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $11 {In fact, Black may even be better in the
long run due to better pawn structure.} *

