{[%evp 0,28,28,18,72,43,53,53,59,29,30,3,23,29,29,29,25,10,9,18,21,37,28,22,40,
18,18,13,3,4,30]} 1. e4 c6 2. d3 e5 $5 {Just as in the first two chapters, I
would like to suggest an original way to play against this variation.} (2... d5
{is the main move.}) 3. Nf3 {White's main approach is to set up a King's
Indian Attack (KIA).} (3. d4 {is a waste of tempo, so Black should have no
problems after} exd4 4. Qxd4 d5 $1 $146 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. exd5 (6. Nc3 Be6 $1 {
[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black's development is easy and natural with Be7 and 0-0,
so I don't see any way how White can pose some problems in the opening.}) 6...
cxd5 {leads to a good version of the Isolani.} 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. O-O Be7 $11 {
and Black has an ideal piece development for this type of position, while
White also has to waste a tempo with his queen.}) ({With} 3. Nd2 {White would
also like to play the KIA setup. However, this move order is maybe a little
bit less accurate than 3.Nf3, as here Black has an additional option to
develop his knight to e7.} g6 $5 4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. g3 d6 $5 6. Bg2 Ne7 ({Black
can also transpose to the main line with} 6... Nf6) 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 {and here
I would recommend} c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] to develop the knight to the most active
square c6. Once again, we are transposing into some kind of Sicilian position
where Black should not be worse.}) ({A Vienna game continuation is} 3. f4 exf4
4. Bxf4 {when Black can use his c6-pawn to comfortably play} d5 {as usual.} 5.
Nd2 (5. Qe2 {This move is dubious due to} Be7 $1 $146 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Ngf3 O-O 8.
O-O-O c5 $15) 5... Nf6 $5 $146 {This new move gives Black completely adequate
play. Possibilities are:} 6. e5 ({and} 6. Ngf3 Be7 7. e5 Nh5 8. Be3 f6 9. Be2
fxe5 10. Nxe5 Nf6 11. O-O O-O {Black is fine.}) 6... Nfd7 7. d4 c5 8. Qf3 Nc6
9. Qxd5 Be7 {Black just wants to complete his development and destroy White's
too advanced pawn center.} 10. O-O-O cxd4 11. Ngf3 O-O 12. Nxd4 Ndxe5 $11) (3.
g3 {This gives Black a choice regarding the placement of his bishop. In this
case, we might as well try the more active} Bc5 $5 (3... Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. Nf3
Bg7 {transposes to main line.}) 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 {
with a balanced middlegame. It is always good to surprise our opponent, so I
would like to deviate from theoretical paths early with} Re8 $146 8. c3 a5 9.
Re1 (9. Nc4 b5 10. Ne3 a4 {Black is fine.}) 9... Nbd7 10. d4 Bb6 {the idea is
to answer} 11. Nc4 ({In case of} 11. a4 {Black can play in the spirit of
Italian opening} exd4 12. cxd4 Nf8 {putting pressure on both central pawns.}) {
with} 11... Bc7 {and if} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc7d6]} 13. Nfxe5
dxe5 {[%csl Gb6,Gc7,Gd6][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8e6] Black is doing fine and could
slowly take over the initiative in the symmetrical position.}) 3... Nf6 4. Nbd2
d6 5. g3 {Against KIA, I would recommend the following setup:} g6 $5 6. Bg2 Bg7
7. O-O O-O 8. c3 (8. a4 a5 ({It is also reasonable to play} 8... c5 $5 {
[%cal Gb8c6] transposing to a variation from a closed sicilian, only one tempo
down. I don't think that this is too important in this type of position. The
knight will be developed actively to c6, bishop to e6, etc., and Black will be
doing fine.}) 9. Re1 ({In case of} 9. Nc4 {we can expel the knight from c4 with
} b5 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Ne3 Nc6 {and Black should be doing well in a complex
middlegame.}) 9... Re8 10. c3 ({Once again,} 10. Nc4 {can be met with} b5 $5
$146 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Ne3 Nc6 ({or} 12... Na6 {planning to put the knight on
c5.})) {This attempt to break symmetry deserves attention.} 10... Qc7 $5 $146 (
{Black could continue repeating after White with} 10... Nbd7 $146 {when} 11. d4
{would lead to a slight central advantage for White. In that case, we could
answer with a flank attack:} b5 12. Qc2 Nb6 $5 13. b3 Qc7 14. Bf1 bxa4 15. bxa4
Be6 {and while, objectively speaking, Black should be okay, I wouldn't like to
play such a position that much, so I would prefer 10...Qc7.}) 11. d4 (11. Nc4
b5 $11) 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 ({In case of} 12. cxd4 {we can use the weakness of
b4-square to deploy our knight:} Na6 13. e5 Nd5 14. Nc4 dxe5 15. dxe5 Bg4 {
[%csl Gb4][%cal Ga8d8,Ga6b4,Ga6c5,Gd5b4] and Black has excellent piece play.})
12... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] with a complex Philidor type of middlegame ahead.
Some of White pieces are not placed ideally, while Black has a typical setup
with many dynamic options, including Nd7-c5 or Nb6/d6-d5.} (12... Bg4 $5 13. f3
Bc8 {provoking f3 weakness, is also interesting.})) (8. Re1 Re8 9. c3 {
transposes to 8.c3}) 8... Re8 9. Re1 (9. a4 a5 {is likely to transpose to 8.a4
eventually.}) 9... b5 $5 $146 {I think that this space-grabbing makes sense as
