{[%evp 0,30,15,25,69,20,20,12,12,16,16,-18,-1,7,-8,0,-14,-11,1,1,7,8,7,0,8,9,
21,3,26,-1,-1,4,1]} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ {
In this and next chapter we analyze White's check on move 5. His idea is to
force one of Black pieces to d7, which blocks the queen, so it becomes more
difficult to retrieve the d5-pawn. I feel like this check only helps Black,
because in many positions our knight aims to reach d5-square via b6. So, Black
should be patient and try to win back d5-pawn gradually, rather than
immediately.} Nbd7 6. Nc3 (6. Nf3 {This move is a bit tricky. We should make
sure to insert} a6 $1 {before taking on d5, so that we can break the pin and
secure the knight's position in the center, as Wojtaszek did in the following
game:} 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. O-O Nxd5 10. d4 e6 $15 {Black had a very
comfortable position in the game Artemiev,V - Wojtaszek,R 2015.}) 6... a6 $5 {
In the same spirit as in 6.Nf3 variation.} 7. Qa4 {This is the most testing
move, keeping the pin.} (7. Ba4 {is similar to 6.Nf3, giving Black a good
position after:} b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. Nf3 b4 10. Na4 {after both ...Nd5 or ...Bd5
Black has comfortable play.}) (7. Be2 {is similarly ineffective. Black simply
continues:} b5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb5b4,Gf6d5]} 8. d4 b4 9. Na4 Nxd5 10. Nf3 e6
11. O-O Be7 $15 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8,Ya6a5,Yc8a6] with excellent
control over d5-square. Black is already slightly better.}) ({White can hardly
pose any problems by giving up the bishop pair with} 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Nf3 ({
If White tries to desparately hold on to his extra pawn with} 8. Qb3 $6 {
he would lose the right to castle after} Qg4 $1 9. Kf1 b5 {and Black would
have compensation, at least.} 10. Nf3 e6 $1 {Black is inviting opening of the
center.} ({Another attractive option is} 10... Bb7 11. d4 {when one possible
variation is:} Qf5 $146 12. Ne5 Rd8 13. a4 Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxd5 15. Ng3 Qxe5 16.
Qxb5+ axb5 17. dxe5 bxa4 18. Rxa4 e6 {and Black has enough compensation for
the pawn.}) 11. d4 Be7 $5 $146 {Black will castle and assert his dominance on
the light squares, so he should definitely have the upper hand.}) 8... Nxd5 9.
O-O {This is the best move order.} (9. d4 {allows} Qe6+ $1 10. Ne2 g6 {and
only Black can be better.}) 9... b5 (9... f6 $5 {is a typical idea, clearing
safe f7-square for the king, while preventing moves like Nf3-e5.} 10. Qb3 e6
11. Re1 Kf7 12. d3 b5 {and Black should be OK. Personally, I would prefer to
play 9...b5.}) 10. Ne5 Nxc3 {This is an important inclusion.} 11. dxc3 Qxd1 12.
Rxd1 f6 13. Nc6 Bd7 14. Na5 e5 15. Be3 Be7 {and Black has no problems in the
arising endgame as he moves his bishop to e6, king to f7, and connects his
rooks.}) 7... g6 {Another reasonable option is 7...Rb8. The text move seems
less time-consuming.} 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd7b6] Now White has to do
something with his bishop on b5.} 10. Bxd7 ({In case of} 10. Be2 Nb6 11. Qh4
Nbxd5 {It becomes obvious that White has lost too much time with his queen and
bishop. Black should be simply better after} 12. d4 Bf5 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5]
with easy play.}) {Among three possible recaptures, I prefer} 10... Nxd7 {
because it keeps the most tension in the position. The plan is to recoup the
pawn with b5, Nb6, Bb7, etc.} 11. Qh4 {White avoids the tempo on the queen,
though this has cost him some more time. Black gets his pawn back with} Nf6 12.
d4 Nxd5 13. Bh6 ({In case of the exchange on d5 first,} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Bh6 {
it is very important to play} f6 $5 $146 {which limits mobility of white
knight. After} 15. Rfe1 Re8 {[%csl Gc8] Black should enjoy a slight advantage
thanks to his light-squared bishop and isolated d-pawn.}) 13... Bf6 $5 $146 {
This new move might be an improvement. It surely keeps more tension in the
position.} 14. Qe4 ({There is nothing to be afraid of in case of} 14. Ng5 Re8
$17 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8f5,Gd5c3,Gd8d5] In fact, White pieces look stuck on
the kingside.}) ({If White insists with the bishops exchange, we can simply
play} 14. Bg5 Be6 $1 {and Black seems to be slightly better thanks to strong
control of the square in front of the isolated pawn.}) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Re8
{[%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Gc8e6] with a slight positional advantage in the view of
blockade of White's hanging pawn pair after Be6, b5, Rc8, etc.} *

