1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 {In this chapter, we look at the
other check} 5. Qa4+ {Here, the most popular reply is 5...Nbd7, with a similar
idea to the previous chapter: bring the knight to b6 and take on d5. However,
here we have a strong new idea that can be a big surprise for your opponent.}
Bd7 {This is not the new move, but the next one.} 6. Qb3 {Simultaneously
defending on d5 and attacking on b7. Now Black shows his real idea:} e6 $3 $146
{As we will see, Black is not ready to sacrifice only a few pawns, but also a
full rook! In return, he would get an enormous lead in development.} 7. Qxb7 {
This is the principled continuation. White has a couple of other options, but
they can not trouble Black.} (7. Nc3 $6 Nxd5 $5 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 8. Nxd5 exd5 9.
Nf3 Bd6 10. Qxd5 Bc6 {and black bishops are extremely powerful. White should
probably force the exchange of queens with} 11. Qg5 Qxg5 12. Nxg5 O-O 13. d4
Nd7 {when it is difficult to imagine White keeping his extra pawn considering
his poor development. I believe that Black's initiative should provide him
with more than just compensation for the pawn.}) ({Another way to win the pawn
is} 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. Bc4 {developing a piece and trading strong black bishop at
the same time makes the most sense.} ({This time, White should not take on b7} 
8. Qxb7 $2 {because after} Nbd7 {Black is nearly winning, as we can see in
sample lines below:} 9. d4 ({It would be a big mistake to play a natural move} 
9. Nf3 {because it takes away f3-square from the queen, so now Black has a
very strong move:} a6 $3 {[%cal Gd7c5] taking away b5-square and threatening
to trap the queen with Be6-d5 or Nd7-c5.} 10. Bxa6 Be7 $1 {[%csl Ge8][%cal
Ge8f8] Three pawns down, Black calmly completes his development! The idea is
to vacate a square for the king, so that he could finally play Nd7-c5. White's
problem is that he has no way to prevent loss of material as his pieces on the
queenside are virtually trapped.} 11. O-O Nc5 12. Bb5+ Kf8 $19 {[%csl Rb7]})
9... Rb8 10. Qxa7 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Qc8 12. Nc3 Ra8 $19 {and the queen is trapped
again.}) (8. Qa4+ {is also an option, but does not change much - White still
suffers because of his lag in development.} Bd7 $5 {...Nbd7 and ...Nc6 also
promise Black good play.} 9. Qd1 Bc6 10. Nf3 {and here Black can compromise
White's pawn structure with:} Qe7+ $5 11. Qe2 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Rd2,
Rf2,Rf3,Rh2][%cal Gc6d4] with an obvious positional advantage for Black.}) 8...
Bxc4 $1 9. Qxc4 Nc6 10. Nf3 {White is one move short from fully completing his
kingside development, but Black can prevent it with} Qe7+ $1 11. Kf1 ({The
point is that} 11. Qe2 $2 {fails to} Nb4 $17 {[%csl Gb4,Gc2,Gd3][%cal Gb4d3,
Gb4c2]}) 11... Qd7 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] and having uncastled white
king, Black can proceed to complete his own development with Be7, 0-0,
continuing to put the pressure on White's position, with full compensation for
the sacrificed pawn.}) 7... exd5 $1 {This is all a part of the plan!} 8. Qxa8 (
{In case of} 8. Bb5 {Black continues} Bd6 {and White can not touch the rook on
a8 anymore. In that case, White is only up a pawn, and Black would surely have
enough compensation thanks to his better development.}) 8... Bc5 {[%cal Gd7c6]
Protecting the a-pawn and threatening to trap the queen with 9...Bc6.} 9. Qb7 {
Virtually, the only move. White has made 5 moves with his queen already and
completely neglected his development. This can hardly be good for him.} (9. d4
$2 {is a tactical attempt which fails after} Bc6 $1 10. Bb5 ({as well as} 10.
Qxc6+ Nxc6 11. dxc5 O-O {If we just count the material, White is winning, but
just take a look at his pieces - none of them has been developed and it is
move 11! Black obtains a huge initiative after:} 12. Nf3 Re8+ 13. Be2 Qa5+ 14.
Nbd2 Qa6 $17) 10... Bxb5 11. dxc5 {since Black has an intermediate check} Qe7+
$1 12. Be3 O-O {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gb5c6] trapping the queen on a8.}) 9... Bb6 $1
{[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd7c6] The key move in Black's trapping concept. White queen
has nowhere to go.} 10. a4 $1 {[%cal Rd7c6,Rf1b5] Once again, White has only
one move to stay in the game. He plans to parry...Bc6 threat with Bb5, pinning
the bishop. Thus, Black renews the threat with} O-O {[%cal Gd7c6] It is
interesting to note that Black keeps making threats with useful developing
moves, while White has to make time-consuming and unnatural moves to deflect
these threats. Incredibly, out of 10 moves in the opening, White has made 5
with his pawns and 5 with the queen! The situation of other white pieces is
very poor.} 11. Bb5 $8 Re8+ 12. Ne2 Bxb5 $1 {I found this to be the most
accurate way to go after the queen.} ({Another possibility is} 12... Rxe2+ {
when White is forced to take back with the bishop} 13. Bxe2 ({since} 13. Kxe2
$4 {is refuted nicely with} Qe7+ 14. Kd1 Bg4+ {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge7b7]}) 13...
Bc6 14. Qxb6 Qxb6 {Black has returned most of his material, though after
analyzing the position a bit further, I have come to the conclusion that the
alternative 12...Bb5 is a better choice for Black.}) 13. axb5 Re7 {Sending the
queen back to the corner.} 14. Qa8 (14. Qxe7 $2 Qxe7 $17 {[%csl Re2] would be
a much worse version of a similar position from 12...Rxe2 variation.}) 14...
Ne8 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ge8c7] The key idea. Black pieces are coordinating
perfectly to trap the queen, while White is still struggling to complete his
development.} 15. Nbc3 ({The other option is} 15. O-O {when draw by repetition
is the most objective outcome:} Nc7 16. Qb7 Nxb5 17. Qa8 ({In case of} 17. Qxe7
Qxe7 $17 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1] it will be difficult for White to develop in a
comfortable way.}) 17... Nc7 18. Qb7 Nb5 $11) 15... Nc7 16. Qb7 Nxb5 17. Qxe7 {
This would be White's attempt to play for something more.} ({Obviously, it
would be a quick draw after} 17. Qa8 Nc7 18. Qb7 Nb5 $11) 17... Qxe7 18. Nxb5
d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d3] Another unexpectedly strong move in this variation. It
turns out that White can not keep his extra piece as both his knights are
placed awkwardly.} 19. d3 (19. Kd1 $2 {fails to} d3 20. Ned4 (20. Nec3 Bxf2 $19
{[%csl Rd1][%cal Ge7e6,Ge6g4,Ge6b3]}) 20... Qd7 $19 {[%csl Rd4]}) (19. Ra3 {
is the only way to stop d4-d3 without losing material, but White's problem is
that his pieces are so uncoordinated that he can't do anything useful with
them and Black even has time for moves like} h5 $3 {[%csl Rb5] We can take a
look at a couple of options for White:} 20. d3 (20. Rb3 Nc6 21. Na3 d3 $5 22.
Rxd3 Qe4 $1 23. Rb3 Nd4 24. Re3 Qxg2 $15 {[%cal Gd4f3]}) 20... Qb4+ 21. Nbc3
dxc3 22. bxc3 Qg4 23. Rg1 $8 Qg6 {[%csl Rd3]} 24. d4 Qc2 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga7a5,
Gb8c6] White's piece coordination is awful.}) 19... Qb4+ 20. Nbc3 dxc3 21. bxc3
Qg4 {with an unclear position.} *

[Event "?"]
