1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {This is the main
alternative to the main line of the Panov attack - 6.Nf3. White tries to put
immediate pressure on d5-pawn. Black usually solve this issue with 6...Be6, 6..
.dxc4, or simply 6...e6. However, I would like to propose a completely
different approach - ignore White's threat and play:} g6 $5 {For all intents
and purposes, this is a novelty. Although this move was tried in two games,
they were on a very low level and likely not well-prepared, so we can consider
this as a completely new idea at a very early stage of the game.  This pawn
sacrifice in the spirit of 4.Bg5 variation of Gruenfeld defense offers a new
area to explore and I have tried to cover as much ground as possible in my
analysis. Of course, it is possible to explore this interesting idea even more,
especially when new games are played in this line, so I would encourage you to
check the analysis yourself, as well. I believe that this move can also have a
significant surprise value because the opponent would probably see it for the
first time.} 7. Bxf6 {Of course, this is the most principled response.} (7. Nf3
{is more conservative, transposing into Chapter 10 after} Be6 ({though Black
can also continue in the same spirit with} 7... Bg7 $5 8. Bxf6 exf6 $1 9. cxd5
Ne7 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qa4 ({In case of} 11. d6 Nf5 12. Qe2+ Kf8 {Black gets his
pawn back at the expense of not castling. Still this is completely fine for
him after} 13. O-O Nxd6 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gh7h5,Gf8g8,Gg8h7] and
he can connect his rooks after h5, Kg8-h7 maneuver, while the knight on d6 is
a fantastic blocker.}) 11... a6 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Gh8d8,Gd7e8,Ge8f8] and sooner or later Black will be in a position to get his
pawn back.})) (7. Qa4 $5 $146 {is an interesting idea that has not been played
before, threatening to win the piece after Bxf6, cxd5. Therefore, Black has to
protect the pawn with} Be6 $1 8. Nge2 Bg7 9. Nf4 (9. Rd1 {is not as critical.
Black has time to improve his bishop with} Bd7 $5 {and now:} 10. cxd5 Na5 {
gives Black very good compensation for the pawn.} 11. Qa3 ({The queen is more
exposed on} 11. Qb4 O-O $15 {with ideas like ...Rc8-c4 or ...Re8, Bf8!}) 11...
Nc4 12. Qb3 Na5 13. Qa3 Nc4 14. Qb3 {and here Black is spoiled for choice and
he can take the draw or continue with ...Rc8 with good compensation.}) 9... Nd7
$1 {This typical Gruenfeld maneuver is very important, creating counterplay
against the d4-pawn, while breaking the pin on c6-knight at the same time.} 10.
O-O-O {This is the sharpest continuation and also the most critical one.} ({
After several exchanges in the center:} 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. cxd5 Nb6 12. Qa3 exd5
{We get an interesting position. Both sides have pawn weaknesses. A possible
line is:} 13. Bb5 O-O 14. O-O Nxd4 $1 15. Bxe7 Nxb5 16. Nxb5 Bxb2 17. Qb4 a5
18. Qxb2 Qxe7 $15 {when White's compensation can be enough for a draw at most.}
) (10. cxd5 {is simply answered with} Nb6 11. Qa3 Bxd5 12. Nfxd5 Nxd5 $15 {
[%csl Rd4,Gd5] and Black is already better due to weak isolated pawn on d4.})
10... Nb6 11. Qa3 Nxd4 {The position has become double-edged. White has
several options:} 12. cxd5 (12. c5 {leads to some interesting complications:}
h6 $1 13. cxb6 hxg5 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 15. Nxd5 axb6 $1 (15... Kf8 {is also
possible if you don't want to sacrifice your queen.}) 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. Rxd8+
Rxd8 $15 {[%cal Ge8f8,Gh8h4] and for the queen, Black has obtained enough
material, and I would argue that he also has a better position thanks to his
strong bishop on f6 and exposed white king.}) (12. Nfxd5 {also leads to an
interesting position, although a bit more quiet:} Bxd5 $1 13. cxd5 h6 $1 14.
Be3 Nf5 15. Bb5+ Kf8 $5 16. Bc5 Nd6 {[%cal Gf8g8,Gg8h7] and Black has a
typical solid blockade on d6. If I would have to pick sides, I would prefer
Black in such a position because of the long-term positional potential.}) 12...
Bf5 $1 13. Bd3 Rc8 {By castling queenside, White has quickly mobilized his
forces, but this also contains some risks as Black can already target the king
on the c-file.} 14. Bxf5 $1 ({In case of} 14. Rhe1 {Black happily sacrifices
material to obtain the initiative:} O-O $1 15. Bxe7 Qd7 16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. Qa5 (
