{[%evp 0,30,19,38,60,69,57,47,49,37,37,15,26,20,38,8,34,26,38,36,12,31,35,22,
17,-7,7,5,13,13,15,9,13]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 {Lately this
simple system became fashionable for White. It does not require memorization
of long theoretical lines and the arising positions are fairly simple,
requiring from White only understanding of a few basic pawn structures and
piece maneuvers. It is not without some poison, though, because White wants to
prevent Black from developing his light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.
If he could succeed in this, he would have better chances in the middlegame
because of the potential kingside attack. All this being said, Black usually
gets a reasonable position out of the opening with simple developing moves
that facilitate development of his bishop to g4 or f5.} Nc6 5. c3 (5. Nf3 {
is inaccurate as it allows Black to develop his bishop without much effort.}
Bg4 6. c3 Qc7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Rc1f4] If it is possible to stop White's Bf4,
then why not?} 7. O-O (7. h3 Bh5 8. Be3 {is quite tame, allowing Black to
achieve his desired piece setup in this pawn structure:} e6 9. Nbd2 Bd6 {
[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8,Yb7b5] We should remember that Black's ideal setup involves
development of the knight to e7, which is, in fact, Botvinnik's setup in the
QGD, only with colores reversed. After that, Black has a clear plan: minority
attack by means of ...b5 - ...b4.}) (7. Nbd2 {is quite similar. Black easily
achieves his ideal piece development:} e6 8. O-O (8. Nf1 {Black should be
alert to knight's maneuver to g3, when h2-h3 threatens to win the bishop pair
and the knight can actually be useful in attack on g3. Therefore, we act
prophylactically by exchanging the bishop for White's strongest attacking
piece - Bd3:} Bh5 {That's the reason it's logical to go like this.} 9. Ng3 Bg6
10. O-O Bd6 11. Re1 Nge7 {and Black is perfectly fine.}) 8... Bd6 9. h3 Bh5 10.
Re1 Nge7 {Once again, we have reached Botvinnik's setup.} 11. Nf1 {Here we
have two choices:} Bg6 {This is the traditional way.} ({It is also possible to
keep some tension in the position with} 11... h6 {avoiding the sacrifice on h7
(see 11...0-0?)} 12. Be2 O-O 13. Nh4 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Rae8 {and Black is okay.
His plan is to move the knight from e7 and prepare ...f6-...e5 break, fully
according to Botvinnik's recommendation in such positions.}) (11... O-O $2 {
falls for:} 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Kg6 14. g4 {and White wins.}) 12. Ne3 O-O
13. Ng4 {With this time-consuming maneuver, White has managed to reach
important e5-square with his knights. As a means of counterplay, Black should
initiate the well-known minority attack on the other side of the board:} a6 14.
Nge5 Bxe5 $5 $146 {This exchange makes sense from a positional point of view
as the dark-squared bishop was not a particularly useful piece in this pawn
structure.} 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 b5 {In such a position, the
knight can prove to be a better piece than the dark-squared bishop, not to
mention that Black already has very good counterplay on the queenside.}) 7...
e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7] After this, the game usually transposes to one of
White's choices on move 7. For example:} 8. Re1 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7] and then 7.
h3 or 7.Nbd2 just transposes into the mentioned lines.}) (5. Ne2 {is quite
inaccurate, as it allows Black to play:} Nb4 $1 {forcing the exchange of
light-squared bishops.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. c3 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8f6,
Gf8d6] and Black clearly has no problems.}) 5... Nf6 6. Bf4 {It is important
to note that this exact position can arise from the London system move order:
1.d4-d5 2.Bf4-c5 3.e3-cd4 4.ed4-Nc6 5.c3-Nf6 6.Bd3, making this database
suitable for your Black repertoire against the London, as well.} ({In case of} 
6. Ne2 {6...Bg4 is not so effective because the pin is not so strong and the
