best move in a position where White has three good-looking captures is an
intermediate move like this.} ({The first question in this double-edged
position is what happens in case of} 8. Qxb7 {The answer is:} Rb8 $1 $146 9.
Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qa6 exf4 {[%csl Rb2]} 11. Nf3 Rxb2 12. O-O Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]
with a complicated position where Black should be okay thanks to his activity.}
) ({The second capture} 8. Bxe5 {runs into} Qe7 $1 9. Ne2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5
11. h3 $5 $146 ({It is extremely risky to go pawn-grabbing with exposed king
on e1:} 11. Qxb7 $2 Rb8 12. Qxa7 Bxe2 $1 $146 13. Bxe2 Rxb2 14. Nd2 Bd6 $1 15.
Qa8+ {and now Black has a stunning win:} Ke7 $3 16. Qa7+ (16. Qxh8 $4 Rxd2 $1
17. Kxd2 Ne4+ 18. Kd1 Qxc3 $19 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gc3d2]}) 16... Ke6 $1 $19 {
[%csl Rc3,Rd2,Re1,Re2][%cal Gh8b8]}) 11... Bd7 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8] Black has
an easy development and the bishop pair, so I like his chances.}) ({Finally,
against} 8. dxe5 {Black has} Nh5 {and the point is that White can not keep the
pawn e5-defended any more, after which ...Nxe5 wins the key tempo on Bd3.} 9.
Be3 (9. Bg3 {should not be problematic for Black at all.} Nxg3 10. hxg3 Nxe5
11. Bb5+ Nc6 12. Be2 Bc8 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yf8c5,Gd5d4] GM David Navara
played this in a blitz game and Black was okay.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 {
We got the position with Isolani, which is sometimes better for White, but in
this case Black looks active enough. Let us look at the possibilities:} 11. Nd2
(11. Be2 Nf6 $1 $146 {This is, of course, better than taking on e2 and
developing White's knight in the process. The only problem might be the
capture on b7, which is analyzed below.} 12. Nd2 ({If} 12. Qxb7 $146 {Black
equalizes with a precise sequence:} Bd7 13. Bf4 Bc5 $1 14. Bc7 Bxf2+ $1 15.
Kxf2 Ne4+ 16. Ke1 Qg5 17. Qxa8+ Ke7 18. Qxh8 Qc1+ 19. Bd1 Qe3+ 20. Be2 Qc1+ $11
) 12... Qd7 13. Ngf3 Bd6 14. O-O O-O $11 {and this looks like a nice Tarrasch
French for Black.}) ({Another option is} 11. h3 {chasing the bishop back.
After the normal development} Be6 12. Qd1 Nf6 13. Nf3 Bd6 14. O-O O-O 15. Nbd2
a6 16. Bd3 Re8 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gd8d6,Ye6d7,Yd8c7,Yf6e4,Yd6f4] and Black has many
active options, such as ...Bc7, ...Qd6, ...Ne4 etc.}) 11... Be6 12. Qa4 Qc7 13.
Ngf3 Bd6 14. O-O O-O {we get a Tarrasch Isolani type of position that was
discussed in detail by GM Mihail Marin in his Modern Chess: French repertoire.}
) 8... Na5 $1 {It is essential to remember this move because we may end up
being worse otherwise. One way to remember is that in case of dxe5 king's
knight goes to the rim (Nh5) and in case of h3, queens knight goes to the rim 
(Na5).} 9. Qc2 exf4 (9... Bd1 $5 {is a peculiar move, which is playable, but
hasn't been explored yet. Its idea is to prevent opening of the h-file, which
happens in the main line.}) 10. hxg4 Nxg4 {An unusual position. Both sides
still have to be precise.} 11. Qe2+ ({A more materialistic option for White is
} 11. Rxh7 Rxh7 12. Bb5+ {An important intermezzo.} Nc6 13. Qxh7 {Now, we can
improve the current theory with:} Qb6 $5 $146 14. Qd3 Bd6 15. Nd2 Kf8 16. Qh3
$1 {[%csl Re1,Gg4][%cal Gg4f2,Re1c1]} Nh6 17. a4 a6 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 {How to
assess this position? Black has structural weaknesses, but some dynamic
factors are in his favor, such as relatively exposed white king and potential
weakness on a4. So I would call this position roughly balanced.}) 11... Qe7 12.
Nh3 f3 {The f-pawn is lost, so we might as well use it to provoke some
weaknesses.} 13. Qxe7+ ({The endgame after} 13. gxf3 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nf6 15. Nd2
Bd6 {is quite unusual. White has semi-open files on the kingside, so it is
kind of dynamically balanced. For example:} 16. Rag1 O-O 17. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3]}
b5 18. Ne3 (18. f4 g6 {should also be okay for Black.}) 18... g6 19. Rg5 (19.
Nf5 Rfe8+ 20. Kd2 Bf8 {is harmless for Black.}) 19... h6 {This weakens g6- and
h6-pawns, but it had to be played.} 20. Rgg1 Rfe8 $1 {White can try to
sacrifice on g6, but this only leada to equality.}) 13... Bxe7 14. g3 {All of
this has been seen in several games of strong players. Here, I would recommend
a new move:} g6 $5 $146 15. Nd2 O-O {[%cal Gg8g7,Ge7d6]} 16. Nxf3 Bd6 {The
only possible problem for Black in this endgame is the isolated d-pawn;
however, it is difficult to see how White can attack this pawn since Ng4 and
Bd6 hold e3- and f4-squares, respectively. I don't believe that this could be
a problematic position for Black.} *

