{[%evp 0,24,19,38,60,69,57,47,49,43,51,22,29,34,5,2,7,3,-3,-17,-18,-12,-36,-43,
-38,-34,-25] In this chapter, we mainly look at exchange variation of the Caro
Kann with Nf3 move.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 {is another move
order, when the most popular move is} 4. Ne5 (4. Bb5+ Bd7 {looks the simplest.}
(4... Nc6 {is also possible. White can win the bishop pair with} 5. Ne5 Bd7 6.
Nxd7 Qxd7 7. d4 {but in this kind of position, Black does not mind swapping
off his light-squared bishop.} a6 {It is important to play this move exactly
now because White can not retreat the bishop to its ideal square d3. It will
cost him a tempo to do that later in the game.} (7... e6 {is inaccurate due to}
8. c3 a6 9. Bd3) 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O ({Also after} 9. c3 Nf6 10. Nd2 Bd6 11. Nf3
O-O 12. O-O b5 13. a3 Na5 {Black has no problems.}) 9... Bd6 10. c3 Qc7 {
As I mentioned before, this is usually the best square for black queen. It is
also good to provoke a slight weakness in White's pawn structure.} ({Once
again, timing is important. In case of} 10... Nf6 11. Nd2 Qc7 {White
conveniently protects the pawn with} 12. Nf3) 11. g3 $1 (11. h3 {weakens dark
squares, so 11.g3 should be preferred. Black has a similar plan as in the main
line:} Nf6 $146 12. Be3 O-O 13. Nd2 b5 {with a good position.}) 11... Nf6 12.
Nd2 {Knight's maneuver to f3 solidifies White's position. However, it takes
some time, so after} O-O 13. Nf3 b5 {Black is the first one to start active
operations. His minority attack is something that White needs to address in
one way or another - otherwise he will be saddled with a backward pawn on c3
or an isolated pawn on d4. In the following game, White tried} 14. a4 b4 15. c4
{and the position was balanced after} dxc4 16. Bxc4 Rfd8 17. Qe2 Qb7 18. Bg5
Be7 19. Rad1 Nd5 {1/2 (62)-1/2 (62) Santos Latasa,J (2549)-Kuzubov,Y (2689)
Batumi GEO 2018}) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. O-O Nc6 7. d4 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7]} 8. Bf4
Bd6 {and I don't see how Black can have problems here.}) {After} 4... a6 $1 5.
d4 Nc6 {we transpose into 2.d4 (main line) - 5.Ne5 variation.}) 2... d5 3. exd5
cxd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 ({An interesting way to stop ...Bg4 is} 5. Ne5 {Now,
capturing the knight would not be so good because Black could not develop his
bishop outside the pawn chain. As mentioned in an earlier instance of Nf3-e5,
we can prevent Bb5 with} a6 $5 {This is not the only way to handle this line,
but I think that it makes sense to prevent Bb5 move.} (5... Nxe5 6. dxe5 Bf5 $2
{does not work due to} 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Qxd5 Qa5+ 9. Nc3) 6. c3 (6. Be2 {is an
interesting waiting move by GM Safarli. However, in this case Black can
actually play} Nxe5 $5 $146 7. dxe5 Bf5 {because b5-square has been covered,
so White does not have a check. Black would have a pleasant position if the
structure remains like this, so White should probably play c2-c4 at some point
to trade the strong d5-pawn.} 8. c4 (8. O-O e6 9. c4 Ne7 10. Bf3 Rc8 11. cxd5
Nxd5 {looks balanced.}) 8... dxc4 $1 9. Nd2 b5 {Black challenges White to
prove his compensation for the pawn.} 10. a4 Rb8 11. axb5 axb5 12. O-O e6 13.
b3 c3 14. Nf3 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Bc5 $1 {with an interesting position. Possible
variations are:} 16. Ra5 ({or} 16. Nd4 c2 17. Rd2 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 b4 {the
c2-pawn is very strong, but White still has a lead in development.}) 16... c2
17. Rd2 Ne7 18. Bxb5+ Kf8 19. Bc4 Bb6 20. Ra4 g5 {[%cal Gf8g7] once again, the
position is unclear as boths sides have their trumps.}) (6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3
Nf6 8. h3 e6 {[%cal Gc6c5] should not worry Black, especially once he pushes ..
.c6-c5.}) (6. c4 {is also an option, when it is not advisable to play 6...Bf5.
Simple development should work well here. After all, White has weakened his
d4-pawn with his last move.} e6 7. Nxc6 (7. Be2 Nge7 $1 $146 8. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 9.
Nf3 g6 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Ge7f5] looks like a good setup against
the Isolani.}) 7... bxc6 {The pawn structure is still flexible, reminiscent of
the Nimzo-Indian with colors reversed. Black should keep in mind to develop
his pieces in the following way: Bd6, Ne7.} 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Be2 Ne7 10. Bg5 O-O {
and Black is completely fine. He just needs to develop his light-squared
bishop (...a5, ...Ba6 looks natural). One possible continuation is:} 11. Qd2 h6
$1 $146 12. Bh4 Qc7 $5 13. Bg3 dxc4 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne4 Qc7 $15 {[%csl Rd4]
[%cal Gf8d8,Ga6a5,Gc8a6]}) {Here, we can also play as in 6.Be2 line:} 6... Nxe5
7. dxe5 Bf5 {and Black should be absolutely fine.} 8. Bd3 ({or} 8. Be2 $146 e6
9. Be3 Ne7 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. f4 Be7 {[%csl Gf5] with a solid Caro-Kann setup.})
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 {[%csl Gc5,Ge7,Gf8][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Gf8c5] and
Black completes his development smoothly with ...Bc5, ...Ne7-f5(c6).}) ({
In case of} 5. Bb5 {we can make a subtle move} Qa5+ $5 {forcing White to play}
(5... Bg4 {is the main line.}) 6. Nc3 {and the knight is not placed well on
this square. Now, we develop the bishop outside:} Bg4 7. Bd2 {[%csl Gc7][%cal
Rc3d5]} (7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qg3 {This is the only way to
trouble Black. Otherwise he just completes his development with ...Be7, ...0-0,
etc.} Nh5 $5 {Not the only way, but shows how harmless White's setup is.} 11.
Qh4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7]} 12. Qg3 Nh5 $11 13. Qg5 Nf6 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf6h5] and ...
h6 is coming on the next move. White won't be able to stop ...Nh5 either way.})
7... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Gc7] A precise move before we actually retreat the queen,
preventing Nxd5-c7 fork.} 8. a4 Qd8 $1 {[%csl Rc3] Now, the queen has to
retreat, but that is okay. It has completed its job on a5, forcing the knight
on a clumsy c3-square. We can see that Black was completely fine in the
following GM game:} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e6 11. Ne2 a6 12. Bd3 Nb4 13. O-O Nf6
14. Bxb4 Bxb4 15. g3 Bd6 $11 {Hovhannisyan,R - Petrosyan,M}) 5... Bf5 {
Compared to Chapter 12, White has not played Bd3, so it seems very logical to
develop black bishop to this diagonal.} 6. Bf4 e6 {Once again, we have reached
a position that can also arise from the London system.} 7. Qb3 Qd7 {This is
the most straightforward way to deal with White's threat.} ({A thematic pawn
sacrifice} 7... Bd6 $5 {and}) ({a more quiet} 7... Qc8 {are also possible.}) 8.
Nbd2 ({At the first glance, it may seem like} 8. Bb5 {and 9.Ne5 creates
problems for Black, but he can eliminate this threat with} f6 $5 {preparing
kingside expansion with ...g7-g5, at the same time!} 9. h4 $146 {This move has
not been tried yet, but I think that it is important to stop Black's kingside
expansion.} (9. Bg3 g5 10. h3 h5 $15 {is simply better for Black.}) (9. Nbd2 g5
10. Bg3 h5 11. h3 Nge7 $146 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ga7a6,Ge7g6,Gh5h4,Gf8d6,Gg6f4] is
not much better for White, either. Black controls much more ground that White.}
) (9. O-O {also plays into Black's hands. After} g5 10. Bg3 h5 11. h4 g4 12.
Ne1 {Black has more than one good way to continue:} a6 $5 $146 (12... Bd6 {
trading g3-bishop, should also give Black an edge.}) 13. Be2 O-O-O {[%cal
Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ye6e5,Gf5g6,Ge7f5,Re7g6] and Black has easy play. One option is to
transfer the knight to f5 via e7.}) 9... Nge7 10. Nbd2 a6 11. Be2 Ng6 12. Bg3
Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 $15 {looks very comfortable for Black. He controls the
situation in the center and on the queenside. Possible plans are ...b7-b5-b4
and ...e6-e5.}) (8. Nh4 {is an attempt to win the bishop pair, but it comes at
a price of wasting time in the opening. Black can take advantage of it with:}
Bxb1 $5 $146 (8... Be4 {has been played before, and it looks fine, as well.
However, capture on b1 leads to a good position for Black by force, so let's
just keep it simple.}) 9. Rxb1 f6 {[%cal Gg7g5] Now white pieces are being
pushed back.} 10. Nf3 g5 11. Bg3 h5 12. h4 g4 13. Ng1 O-O-O {[%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f5,
Gf8d6] With a pleasant position for Black. A simple plan to take the
initiative is ...Nh6-f5 and/or ...Bd6.}) (8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. Bxe5 {contains a
one-move threat (10.Bb5) that we can defend against with a simple developing
move} Ne7 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Bg3 Be7 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge8g8] and Black has no
problems whatsoever.}) 8... f6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] Just like in 8.Bb5 line,
this move is the key for Black.} 9. h4 {From the lines we have seen in 9.h3
and 9.Be2, it is clear that White has to make this move.} (9. h3 g5 10. Be3 h5
$1 $146 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ge8c8,Ye8f7] and Black has an advantage whether he
puts his king on f7 or castles queenside.}) (9. Be2 g5 10. Bg3 h5 {looks very
nice for Black.} 11. h3 (11. h4 g4 12. Nh2 Bg6 $146 13. O-O Bh6 14. Qd1 f5 $17
{[%cal Yf5f4,Yg8f6] already gives Black as serious advantage as white pieces
are completely stuck.}) 11... Nge7 12. O-O {and now we can launch an attack
with} h4 $1 $146 13. Bh2 g4 14. hxg4 Bxg4 15. Qd1 h3 {to stop it, White would
have to play} 16. g3 Nf5 $17 {[%csl Rh2] when his bishop on h2 is just a pawn.}
) {Previously, 9...h5 has been played in two games, but I believe that it may
not be necessary and that we can develop more quickly with} 9... Nh6 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gh6f7,Gf8d6] the knight is maneuvered to f7, supporting ...Bd6.} 10. Be2
Nf7 11. O-O Bd6 12. Bxd6 Nxd6 {and Black has achieved a very harmonious setup
without weaknesses, while also managing to trade opponent's most active piece 
(Bf4). The knight on d6 is very nicely placed. Black has a choice of centrla
play with ...e5 and queenside play with ...b5.} *

