1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 {This position can also arise via 1.
d4-d5 2. Bf4-c5 3.e3-cd4 4.ed4 London system. In most cases White will play
Nf3, transposing into Chapter 13. In this chapter, we will look at an
additional option for White where he postpones Nf3.} Nc6 5. c3 (5. Nf3 Bf5 6.
c3 {transposes to Chapter13.}) 5... Bf5 6. Nd2 (6. Bd3 {is not critical. Black
gets a good position after} Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O
Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} ({or} 10... Nf6)) (6. Nf3 e6 7. Nbd2 {transposes to 6.Nd2}
(7. Qb3 {on the other hand, transposes to Chapter13.})) ({Just to make sure
that we cover all possibilities,} 6. Qb3 {also transposes to the previous
chapter after:} Qd7 7. Nf3 ({or} 7. Nd2 e6 8. Ngf3 f6) 7... e6) 6... e6 7. Ngf3
(7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Ngf3 f6 {is another transposition to Chapter 13.}) 7... f6 {
[%cal Gg7g5] This move has been played in a similar position from Chapter 13,
only with queens on b3 and d7. Black benefits from postponing development of
king's knight, since he not only covers e5-square, but also prepares ambitious
pawn expansion ...g5, ...h5.} 8. Nh4 $5 $146 {This is the only independent try}
({compared to} 8. Qb3 Qd7 {- Chapter13.}) {Black can play} 8... g5 {
nevertheless! This leads to complications with mutual chances.} 9. Qh5+ ({
White can also sacrifice a piece with:} 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. Be3 f4 11. Bxf4 gxf4
12. Qh5+ Ke7 $5 13. Bd3 {hoping to take advantage of poorly placed black king.
Therefore, Black should play:} Kd6 $1 14. O-O Kc7 {and the king is fairly safe.
} 15. Rfe1 Qd7 {The position is quite unclear. White has compensation for the
piece in the view of better development. Black's plan is to untangle with ...
Nh6 and ...Rg8/Qg4.}) 9... Kd7 10. g4 Bc2 {A very strange position. Somehow
after} 11. Rc1 gxf4 12. Rxc2 Qe8 {it is relatively balanced. I think that
Black should have no problems after the queen trade.} *

